      <div class="calc-main">
        <h1>📊 Statistics Calculator</h1>
        <p class="calc-intro">Calculate mean, median, mode, range and standard deviation of any dataset instantly.</p>

        <div class="card">
          <label>Enter numbers separated by commas or spaces</label>
          <input type="text" id="stat-nums" placeholder="4, 7, 2, 9, 4, 1, 7, 4" oninput="calcStat()">
          <div class="result-box" id="stat-res">Enter a dataset</div>
          <div style="margin-top:1rem;display:grid;grid-template-columns:repeat(2,1fr);gap:0.75rem" id="stat-grid"></div>
        </div>

        <div style="margin-top:2rem;padding-top:1.5rem;border-top:1px solid var(--border)">
          <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-display);font-size:1.2rem;font-weight:700;margin-bottom:1rem">When to use each measure</h2>
          <p style="color:var(--muted);font-size:0.9rem;line-height:1.8;margin-bottom:0.75rem"><strong>Mean:</strong> Best when data is roughly symmetrical with no extreme outliers. Good for test scores, temperatures.</p>
          <p style="color:var(--muted);font-size:0.9rem;line-height:1.8;margin-bottom:0.75rem"><strong>Median:</strong> Best when data has outliers or is skewed. Better for house prices, incomes where a few very high values distort the mean.</p>
          <p style="color:var(--muted);font-size:0.9rem;line-height:1.8;margin-bottom:0.75rem"><strong>Mode:</strong> Best for categorical data or when you need the most common value. Used in fashion sizes, most popular products.</p>
          <p style="color:var(--muted);font-size:0.9rem;line-height:1.8"><strong>Standard deviation:</strong> Measures how spread out the data is. Low = data clustered near the mean. High = data widely spread.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <aside class="calc-sidebar">
        <div class="card sidebar-card">
          <h2>What is descriptive statistics?</h2>
          <p>Descriptive statistics summarise and describe the main features of a dataset. The key measures are central tendency (mean, median, mode — what is typical) and dispersion (range, standard deviation — how spread out the data is).</p>
        </div>
        <div class="card sidebar-card">
          <h3>Frequently asked questions</h3>
          <details>
            <summary>What is standard deviation?</summary>
            <p>Standard deviation measures how much the values in a dataset vary from the mean. A low standard deviation means values are close to the mean; a high one means they are spread out widely.</p>
          </details>
          <details>
            <summary>Can there be more than one mode?</summary>
            <p>Yes. If two values appear with equal maximum frequency, both are modes (bimodal). If all values are unique, there is no mode.</p>
          </details>
          <details>
            <summary>What is the difference between population and sample standard deviation?</summary>
            <p>This calculator uses population standard deviation (divides by n). Sample standard deviation divides by n−1 and is used when your dataset is a sample of a larger population.</p>
          </details>
        </div>
